{
  "id": "phase-rs_phase_1449",
  "repo_name": "phase-rs/phase",
  "repo_url": "https://github.com/phase-rs/phase",
  "base_commit": "d0ee81399d7ee1588d95ab3382aec3eb4ad330dd",
  "pr_number": 1449,
  "issue_number": 1448,
  "issue_title": "Soulbond pair isn't broken when one effect gains control of both paired creatures (CR 702.95e)",
  "issue_body": "## Summary\n\nA soulbond pair only breaks on a control change if the two creatures end up with *different* controllers. When a single effect gives **both** halves of the pair to the same new player (e.g. Mass Manipulation choosing both), they still share a controller, so `cleanup_invalid_pairs` keeps the pair alive and the soulbond payload (e.g. the +X/+X bonus) stays active for the new controller. Per CR 702.95e the pair must break, because another player gained control of the creatures.\n\nThis is a genuine defect in already-shipped behavior (the soulbond pairing primitive is fully wired and tested), not an unimplemented gap.\n\n## Location\n\n`crates/engine/src/game/pairing.rs`, `cleanup_invalid_pairs` \u2014 the validity predicate.\n\n## Offending code (before)\n\n```rust\nlet valid = obj.zone == Zone::Battlefield\n    && partner.zone == Zone::Battlefield\n    && obj.controller == partner.controller   // <-- compares the two halves to EACH OTHER\n    && obj.card_types.core_types.contains(&CoreType::Creature)\n    && partner.card_types.core_types.contains(&CoreType::Creature)\n    && partner.paired_with == Some(id);\n```\n\nThe doc comment also encoded the wrong rule: *\"\u2026or stops being under the same controller.\"*\n\n## Root cause\n\nThe engine never recorded **who formed the pair**. It only stores `paired_with`, so the only control check available is \"do the two creatures currently share a controller.\" That correctly catches a *single* creature changing control (the controllers then differ), but it cannot detect that *both* creatures left the original controller when they move together to the same new player.\n\nCR 702.95a establishes the pair exists \"for as long as [the creatures] remain creatures on the battlefield **under your control**\" (the soulbond ability controller's), and CR 702.95e breaks the pair if \"**another player gains control of it or the creature it's paired with**.\" The correct invariant is per-creature against the *pairing controller*, not the two creatures against each other.\n\n## CR rules (verified against `docs/MagicCompRules.txt`)\n\n- **CR 702.95a**: a soulbond pair lasts \"for as long as they remain creatures on the battlefield under your control.\"\n- **CR 702.95e**: \"A paired creature becomes unpaired if any of the following occur: another player gains control of it or the creature it's paired with; it or the creature it's paired with stops being a creature; or it or the creature it's paired with leaves the battlefield.\"\n\n## Concrete wrong-vs-correct scenario\n\nPlayer A controls **Wolfir Silverheart** and **Wolfir Avenger**, paired via Silverheart's Soulbond (each gets +4/+4 while paired). Player B casts **Mass Manipulation** with X=2 and gains control of *both* Wolfir creatures.\n\n- **Correct (CR 702.95e):** control of each creature passed to another player \u2192 the pair breaks \u2192 the +4/+4 bonus ends.\n- **Current engine:** after the control-change layer recompute, `cleanup_invalid_pairs` sees both creatures now controlled by B (`obj.controller == partner.controller` still true) \u2192 the pair survives \u2192 B keeps two 9/9 Wolfir. Wrong.\n\nSingle-creature control theft (e.g. **Sower of Temptation** taking one half) is already handled, only because the controllers then differ.\n\n## Fix (implemented)\n\n`crates/engine/src/game/game_object.rs`, `pairing.rs`, `pair_with.rs`, `engine.rs`:\n\n1. New field `GameObject.pair_controller: Option<PlayerId>` \u2014 the player who formed the pair (cleared on battlefield re-entry, alongside `paired_with`).\n2. `pair_objects(state, first, second, controller)` records `pair_controller` on both halves; `break_pair` clears it.\n3. New accessor `pair_controller_of(state, id)`.\n4. `cleanup_invalid_pairs` now requires each creature to still be controlled by its recorded pairing controller:\n   ```rust\n   let self_still_controlled = pair_controller_of(state, id) == Some(obj.controller);\n   let partner_still_controlled = pair_controller_of(state, partner_id) == Some(partner.controller);\n   ```\n   This breaks the pair whenever *either* creature leaves the pairing controller \u2014 including the both-halves-at-once case.\n5. Call sites (`pair_with.rs`, `engine.rs`) pass the soulbond ability controller.\n\n## Tests\n\nExtended `soulbond_pair_breaks_on_leave_control_change_and_stops_being_creature` (in `triggers.rs`, an existing test module) with the both-halves-stolen case: pair under PlayerId(0), set both creatures' controller to PlayerId(1), run `cleanup_invalid_pairs`, assert both become unpaired. Pre-fix this kept the pair; post-fix it breaks. Existing single-control-change, leaves-battlefield, stops-being-creature, and dangling-pair cases still pass.\n\n## Verification\n\nVerified locally (GNU toolchain): `cargo +nightly test -p engine soulbond_pair_breaks` \u2192 1 passed, 0 failed; `cargo clippy -p engine` \u2192 no warnings; `cargo fmt --all` clean. (The MSVC toolchain in this environment lacks a linker; the GNU toolchain was used.)\n\n## Prior art / novelty note\n\nClosely related closed issue: **#367 \"[Engine RFC] Soulbond pair-binding primitive (CR 702.95)\"**, which built the pairing system and explicitly enumerated CR 702.95e and a `ControlChange` unpair reason. That RFC's implementation shipped the single-creature control-break path (with a regression test) but **not** the both-halves-at-once case fixed here. No open issue or PR tracks this defect; searches for `cleanup_invalid_pairs` and `pair_controller` return zero results in both `phase-rs/phase` and `galuis116/phase`.",
  "merged_at": "2026-05-30T06:52:35.000Z",
